<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1398,1928]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="1995" box="[151,328,1398,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis box="[151,328,1398,1424]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">Blabia intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described and remains known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[956,1066,1398,1424]" name="Colombia" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1081,1212,1398,1425]" country="Colombia" name="Magdalena" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">Magdalena</collectingRegion>
). According to Martins &amp; Galileo (1995) (translated): “ 
<taxonomicName box="[563,717,1434,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strandiella">
<emphasis box="[563,717,1434,1460]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. strandiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov, 2019" authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov" authorityYear="2019" box="[847,976,1435,1460]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[847,976,1435,1460]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[992,1055,1435,1461]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, by the antennae relatively short, which surpass the elytral apex only by one antennomere, by the presence of longitudinal yellow pubescent band on center of pronotum, and by the scutellum entirely covered by yellow pubescence. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Breuning, S." box="[1250,1432,1506,1532]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref18470" refString="Breuning, S. (1974) Revision des Rhodopinini americains. Studia Entomologica, 17 (1 - 4), 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1974">Breuning (1974</bibRefCitation>
: 194, 197), the lower eye lobes are distinctly shorter than the gena. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov, 2019" authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov" authorityYear="2019" box="[914,1041,1543,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[914,1041,1543,1568]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1054,1114,1543,1569]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, they are slightly longer than gena. Furthermore, the known geographical distribution of the species is very different.” In fact, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov" authorityYear="2019" box="[1258,1387,1579,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis box="[1258,1387,1579,1604]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,304,1614,1640]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strandiella">
<emphasis box="[151,304,1614,1640]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. strandiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[320,456,1614,1640]" captionStart="FIGURES 68–79. 68–69" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1851,1876]" captionTargetBox="[220,1362,184,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[215,1362,179,1818]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 68–79. 68–69) Blabia intricata, male: 68) Head, frontal view; 69) Head, frontal view, paratype. 70–73) Blabia strandiella, holotype: 70) Head, frontal view; 71) Dorsal habitus; 72) Lateral habitus; 73) Head, oblique view. 74–78) Cycnidolon antonkozlovi, holotype male: 74) Dorsal habitus; 75) Ventral habitus; 76) Lateral habitus; 77) Head, frontal view; 78) Antennomeres III–IV. 79) C. binodosum, holotype, antennomeres III–IV, illustration from Martins (1969). Figures 70–73 by Eugenio H. Nearns (USNM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2702279/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">Figs. 70–73</figureCitation>
) are extremely similar dorsally. However, the information by 
<bibRefCitation author="Breuning, S." box="[1153,1332,1614,1640]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" pagination="12 - 66" refId="ref18410" refString="Breuning, S. (1943) Novae species Cerambycidarum. XII. Folia Zoologica et Hydrobiologica, 12, 12 - 66." type="journal article" year="1943">Breuning (1943</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Breuning, S." box="[1345,1402,1614,1640]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref18470" refString="Breuning, S. (1974) Revision des Rhodopinini americains. Studia Entomologica, 17 (1 - 4), 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1974">1974</bibRefCitation>
) is accurate, and provides a way to separate those two similar species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1398,1928]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">
Nevertheless, Wappes 
<emphasis box="[452,508,1686,1712]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">et al.</emphasis>
(2017) figured two 
<typeStatus box="[732,839,1687,1713]" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">paratypes</typeStatus>
(male and female) showing that the antennae in male are distinctly longer, which agrees with the original description (“Antennae reaching the elytral apex at apex of antennomere VIII (male) or X (female)”). Thus, the information regarding the similarity of the antennae between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos-Silva &amp; Nascimento &amp; Kozlov" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[302,454,1794,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Blabia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strandiella">
<emphasis box="[302,454,1794,1820]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="461">B. strandiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is true only for females.
</paragraph>
